{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_bowheadwhale_ver01/data/sn83045499/00514159555/1929112901/0592.xml":{"full_text":"A MESSAGE OF GENUINE\nIMPORTANCE\nWe announce witii a leeling oi\npride, the biggest and BEST as\nsortment of\nthat have ever come to this coun\ntry- Never before have we made\nsuch preparations lor the holiday\nseason. Never such extradordinary\nvalues. Come in today and visit\nour Toy Department\u2014the thrill\nwill be yours.\nB. M. Behrends Co., Inc\nJuneau's Leading Department Store\nWeather Conditions As Recorded by the U. S.\nWeather Bureau\nI' nrrragt for Juneau anrt vicinity, hew\u2014nine 4 p. m. today:\nFair tonight, Saturday increas ng cloudiness; gentle variable\nv inds becoming southeasterly.\n3,0CAL DATA\nTim\u00ab\nn. m. yest'y\n4 a. m. today\nNoon today\nBarometer Temp.\n.10.31 41\n30.03 45\n30.14 42\nHumidity Wind Velocity Weather\n93 SK 18 Itain\n96 SW 3 Rain\n86 W 2 Pt Cldy\nCARLE AND RADIO REPORTS\n\"YESTERDAY\nEtatlons\nHighest\ntemp.\nUrn row\nNemo\nBethel\nPert Yukon\nTar.ana.\nEagle\nSt. Paul\nDutch Harbor\nilodiak\nCordova\nJuneau\nKetchikan\nF.ince Rupert\nEdmonton\nSeattle\nPortland\n\u00a3an Francisco\n-12\n21\n16\n10\n4 p.m.\ntemp.\n-20\n24\n16\n16\n\nTODA\u2019iT\nLow 4 a.m. 4 a.m. Precip. 4 a.m.\nemp. temp. Velocity 24 hrs. Weather\n20\n34\n38\n42\n42\n50\n52\n52\n24\n50\n43\n72\n16\n34\n36\n38\n40\n41\n50\n52\n20\n48\n4G\n64\n14\n16\n8\n0\n12\n32\n32\n30\n34\n38\n*8\n43\n10\n46\n42\n50\n16\n20\n8\n0\n16\n36\n3G\nSO\n34\n45\n48\n40\n14\n46\n42\n52\n16\n.02\n0\n.08\n0\n.24\n0\n.42\n0\n1.06\n1.20\n.90\n.44\n0\n0\n0\n0\nClear\nCldy\nClear\nClear\nSnow\nCldy\nRain\nClear\nClear\nRain\nRain\nClear\nClear\nCldy\nCldy\nClear\n\u2022Less t\u2019 an 10 miles.\nNOTE\u2014Observations af Barrow, Fort Yukon. Tanana and Eagle\nare made at 8 a. m. and 8 p. m., Juneau time.\nA low pressure area beyond the Aleutians spreads its influence\never most o flhe Territory this morning except in the North where\na moderate high lies. This has g.ven rise to snow over the Seward\nPeninsula and upper Yukon and rain over the Aleutians, and from\nCcrdova to Prince Rupert along the coast. From nearly every Al\naska station warmer temperatures were reported for the past twelve\nhours.\nHIS 30-YEAR STAMP HUNT\nENDS WITH $50,000 SALE\nFred S. Raff with a part of his 30-year stamp collection.\nCHICAGO. Nov. 29\u2014Fred S. Raff,\na bachelor, was a stamp collector\nwhen a lad, but he kept at it for\n30 years and now he has sold his\ncollection for $50,000.\nRaff, who specialized in United\nStates pre-canceled stamps, had\nabout 8,000,000 stamps in his collec\ntion, he estimated. They cost him\naround $10,000 in cash to say noth\ning of the time.\nHe began buying bags of pre\ncanceled stamps, which later grew\nto tons. At one time he bought five\ntons of stamps. It took him sev\neral years to assort them in his\nspare time. The valuable ones he\nkept, the others he sold to dealers\nfor boys\u2019 packets.\n1 WHO'S W HO f\nAND W HERE\nMiss Victoria Spalding of the of\nfice staff of the Biological Survey,\nj is a southbound passenger on the\nNorthwestern. Site will visit friends\nj in Seattle and then continue east\nto see he>- relatives in Toronto,\nCanada\nCharles H. Flory, Commissioner\nfor the Department of Agriculture,\nwho has been visiting Anchorage\nj and Seward on official business for\nthe past three weeks, returned\nhome aboard the steamer North\nwestern.\nFIGHT CARD IS\nCOMPLETED FOR\nLEGION SMOKER\nFive Matches Lined Up for\nAmerican Legion Smok\ner Saturday Night\nCollier vs Silvers, middlcwcights\nSix 3-minute rounds.\nNelson vs Eddie Roberts, 145 pounds\nsix 3-minute rounds.\nLey son vs Itulse, 148 pounds\nfive 3-minute rounds.\nJerry Roberts vs Stan. White\nfour 3-minute rounds.\nDon Smith vs Pete Ervlg\nfour 3-minutc rounds.\nThis is the way the American\nj Legion Smoker card was lined up\ntoday by Matchmaker A1 King,\ni There may have to be a last minute\nchange, but in general this is the\nway the fans can write their tickets\nI if they are inclined to speculate.\nThere may have to be a switch\nin the Hulse-Leyson go, the special\nj event planned by Matchmaker King.\nHulse injured his foot somewhat!\n1 early this week when he stepped on j\na nail. It was uncertain today\nwhether he would be able to go on,\nand there seemed to be no one in\nJ sight to fill his place should the\nI physicians decided he wasn\u2019t in\nshape to scrap.\nIn the other four bouts, however,\nthere should be enough action to\nsatsify even the most rabid fan.\nThese boys are all in good condition\nfor the big mill and everyone is\njrure of winning by the kayo route.\nThe Nelson-Eddie Roberts match\nseems to have a lot of dynamite\nattached to it. Roberts has let\nit be known that Sammy is in for\na good drubbing, something the\nlocal schoolboy hasn't had since he\nfirst donned the leather mittens\nsome two years ago. And Sammy\nis letting Doc\u2019 Silvers, who is train\ning him, do most of the talking.\nDoc\u2019 opines if Roberts whips his\np:ctege, Sam will have to take two\nlickings, the one from Roberts and\nthen another from his trainer. And\nNelson is just confident enough to\nrsk Doc\u2019 to wait another year or\ntwo until he can gain a few more\npounds when he\u2019d be right glad to\nswap punches with him at any old\ntime and place.\nThe two preliminary bouts arc\nsaid to be better than the average.\nAll four boys have been working\nhard in the Legion's fight head\nquarters and are evenly matched.\nNEW ROBOT PILOT KEEPS PLANE ON COURSE\n-\u25a0S-a_Lt\nAssociated Press Photo\nA newly developed Robot pilot was given sn enthusiastic test recently when the trl motored plane\nshown above was flown most of the way from Cleveland to Washington without attention from the\npilot. The device, consisting of a horizontal and vertical gyroscope, measures 14 by 14 by 10 Inches\n\u2022nd ean be placed under the pilot's seat.\nPLUCKY CIRL\nCOMES NORTH\nAS ASSAYEF\nNative of Russia, Aftei\nHard Struggle, Lands\nPosition at Funter\nMIs3 Helen Antonova, accompan\nied by her mother, Elena Antonova\narrived in Juneau on the Alameda\nenroute to Funter Bay, where she\nis to enter the employ of the Ad\nmiralty Gold Mining Company, in\nthe capacity of assayer.\nMiss Antonova is a native oi\nRussia, born near the city of Zeya\nSiberia, which is the mining center\nof that district. She is 25 years\nold, speaks Russian. Japanese, Ger\nman, French and English, has her\ndegree of Bachelor of Science in\nmining and geology from the Uni\nversity of Washington and is a\nmember of the Washington Society\nof Women Engineers.\nWhen a representative of The\nEmpire sought an interview at the\nAlaskan Hotel, he found Miss An\ntonova entertaining visitors, for\nher arrival had been heralded\nabroad in the streets and a num\nber of her fellow countrymen were\nthere to pay their respects.\nMiss Antonova speaks English\nwith scarcely a trace of accent and\nlike many cultured foreigners, she\nhas the knack of expressing her\nself in striking and picturesque\nphrases. Moreover she has the\ncourage to speak frankly about\nsome of the unpleasant chapters of\nher life, and those who listened to\nher animated recital were of the\nopinion that many were of that\norder.\nDangers of Rcvolutoin\nShe had just been graduated\nfrom high school when the Russian\nrevolution of 1917 broke. She and\nher wtfowed mother experienced\nall of the dangers and hardships\nof that upheaval and in time found\ntheir way to Blagoveschensk where\nshe found employment as an actress\nIn the Soviet theatre.\n\u201cIt is what you call home tal\nents,\u2019* sh(j explained.\n\u2022Poorly Paid\nThe repertoire consisted solely of\ndrama and the performances were\nfree to .Communists six days in the\nweek. On Sunday admission was\ncharged and the proceeds divided\namong the performers. This money,\nMiss Antonova said, was about al\nthe pay they received, although\nthey were admitted free to picture\nshows and other amusements con\ntrolled by the Soviet. The company\ngave .Shakespearean plays as well\nas some of the better known Rus\nsian dramas, but a play called\n\u201cHymn to Labor,\u201d the lines of\nwhich were recited in verse, was\nmq3t popular.\n\u2022IVants Education\nMeanwhile Miss Antonova had\nnot despaired of an education. The'\ncolMfcfe At Vladivostok was closed j\nand her petition to the University\nof Moscow; brought no encourage\nment. At lpngth she convinced the\nlocal Commissar that she was en-1\ntitled to 'pursue her education\nabroad, and after the payment of\nLOt) rubles for passport visas she\nind her mother were permitted to1\nleAVe the Country.\nLearns Japanese\nIn Tokio, the Antonovas found\n:hetaiselves eiribarrassecl for want of'\nnohey and Miss Antonova went to\nwork in a Japanese cafe which ca\nered tOj Russians. Here she learned j\nJapanese. There was money in\nM bank when the earthquake\nladte\u2014and then when she tried to\u2019\nIlid the bank somebody had gone\nilong and moved it.\nThe Antonovas next found shelter\nalder the protecting wings of the\nAmerican Red Cross at Kobe, and\n;o0n they landed in Seattle with\nicirlrtg ambitions. Neither could\npeak English but they knew how to\nrash. sew and scrub floors without\nntthictlons and after three months\nif\u00ab struggling and starvation the\nRoir Over Woman Leads\nTo Chilly Swim\nFor One of Battlers\nWhat was reported to have\nbeen a battle between two e\nmen for the favors of a dus- e\nky maid, led to the involun-\na tary ducking of one in the e\no cold waters of Gastineau\nChannel early this morning, o\nand the calling out of the\nI Fire Department for his res-\ncue.\nEd. Donnelley, a mixed-\na blood Indian, was the man\nwho went swimming. Police\ne officers reported he and an-\no other Indian, whose name a\nwas not given them, engaged\nIn a fight over some woman, o\n1 Donnelly, routed, retreated in\ndisorder and fell through an e\nopening in the docks back of\no Roberts Row. He managed o\nto stay afloat until assistance\nwas given him.\nHe was picked up by a\nskiff just as the firemen\nreached the scene. He was\nlanded at the City float and\nwalked into the hands of\n1 Night Patrolman Campen\nwho turned the case over to\nSpecial Officer J. W. Wilson,\na who looks after Indians and\nchecks up on their short- o\n.comings.\nIt was reported to the fire- o\nmen that twe men had fall-\nen overboard from the dock.\ne Put Donnelly said this was a a\nmistake, and that he was\ndown underneath the dock\nall alone.\ngirl found work in a soft drink es\ntablishment where there was gam\ning.\"\nAll this time Miss Antonova had\nbeen trying to decipher the hiero\nglyphics in the Seattle newspapers\nand looking up words in the dic\ntionary. Her knowledge of Japan\nese proved to be an asset when she\npatronized the Japanese markets\nbecause the proprietors were de\nlighted to hear her talk their own\nlanguage. \"They gave me things\ncheap,\" Miss Antonova said.\nHer Chance Comes\nAt last her chance for an educa\ntion came through the help of the\nRussian Student Fund of New York.\nThis fine organization loaned Miss\nAntonova $35 a month and paid\nher tuition at the University of\nWashington. The students are ex\nported to pay back this money\nwithout interest. Miss Antonova\nhas paid back $700 already. i\nDuring her vacations she worked\nfor the Hecla Mining Company, in\nIdaho. They allowed her many;\nopportunities to visit other mines\nin the district. After Ittr gradua-\ntion she applied to several other\nmining companies, but the answer,\nwas always the same: \"Wo don't,\nemploy female help.\"\nAs nothing in that line was to be\nhad immediately she tried her hand\nat selling real estate and mining\nstock. In times of financial stress\nshe fell back on days of \"home!\ntalent,\u201d and sang Russian Gypsy\nsongs to the accompaniment of her j\nguitar in the Club Mauve and the\nMoscow Cafe. The closest she\ncould get to the mining was a posi\ntion as bullion assayer for the Jo- I\nseph Mayer Company, manufactur\ning jewelers in Seattle.\nAlaska Gives a Hand\n\u201cI shall never forget that Alaska\ngave me my first chance to be a\nminer\u2014even if I am a female. Just:\nwait!\u201d\nMiss Antonova spent the greater 1\npart of Wednesday at the Alaska- j\nJuneau in company with mill sup\nerintendent Walter Scott, who\nshowed her over the plant. On\nThanksgiving Day she was the\nguest of honor at a luncheon given\nby Mr. and Mrs. A. P. Kashevaroff.\nShe left on the Margnita at 6\nD\u2019clock last night for Punter Bay. i\n\"I was told in Seattle that large I\nbears walked in the streets of Fun- j\n:er,\u201d she said, as she bid goodbye 1\nto her friends at the dock, \u201cbut 11\nam not afraid. I have my assayer\u2019s\npick, and you know what one may i\ndo,\u2014stick bear in the eye with the\ni sharp point!\"\nYUKON AIRWAYS WILL\nSOON RESUME BUSINESS\n\nThe Yukon Airways Company has\nalready placed an order for a plane\nto take the place of the Queen of\nthe Yukon which was recently\nwrecked and Piiot Patterson was\ni killed.\nJames E. Finnegan, writing from\nMayo for the company, on Novem\nber 10, said it was proposed to re\nsume business immediately. The\nRyan people offered to duplicate the\nQueen of the Yukon for $6500 and\nthe savable parts of the wrecked\nmachine. The sale of stock to get\nthe funds necessary to make the\npurchase was begun immediately at\nMayo, and met with instantaneous\nI success. Dawson also contributed\nstockholders.\nI Mr. Finnegan said: \"large traffic\nI is in sight and the business outlook\nnever better.\u201d\nI The plane Northern Light, now\nI in Yukon, will be used by the\n\u2018Yukon Airways until the new plane\nis received.\nPAY CLERK PORTUIS HERE\n_ I\nPay Clerk P. Portius of the U. S.\nCoast Guard, arrived on the Ala-\nmsda to relieve Chief Pay Clerk T. i\nL. Ryan of the Unalga. Portius\nhas been in the service five years,\nvisited Juneau several times while\ncruising and has many friends here.\nSTART TO PACK\nThe Marlyn Fish Company start\ned to pack at the Juneau Cold Stor\nage Wednesday night, according to\nC. Berg who is here from Ketchi\nkan representing the company. He\nis working a crew of 11 men on the\nnight shift.\nLODE MINING CLAIM LOCA\nTION NOTICES AT THE EMPIRE\nI\nAll the new style\ntendencies in\nSHOES\nAre represented here, in-!\ncludmg the fascinating!\ntwo tone effects. Our\nshoes leave little to be de\nsired for their smartness\nand comfort.\nFrye-Bruhn\nCompany\nFeaturing Frye\u2019s De\nlirious Hams and Bacon\nFresh EASTERN and\nOLYMPIA OYSTERS\nPHONE 38\n\u2014i i\n\u2014H\n\u201cYOUR ALASKA LAUNDRY SERVICE\u201d\n'f\u00b0r\nDry Cleaning and Pressing\nALASKA LAUNDRY\nIn New Building on Shattuck Way\n\u201cTHE LAUNDRY DOES IT BEST\u201d\nSIMMONS\nSprings and Matr esses\nCome in and see the New SIMMONS\n\u201cDeep Sleep99\nand\n\u201cBeautyrest Mattresses\u201d\nTHE\nThomas Hardware Co.\nBuild Your Garage NOW\nA GOOD INVESTMENT AT SMALL COST\nSAVE THE WORRY AND BE SAFE\nLET US FIGURE FOR YOU\nQUALITY and SERVICE\nJuneau Lumber Mills, Inc.\nPHONE 358\nLumber for Every Purpose\nHunters and Prospectors\nTWIN GLACIER CAMP IS NOW OPEN\nBest of accoinmodations for Hunting Parties\nand Prospectors. Reasonable Rates. For\nfurther particulars see\nFRED ORDWAY, Alaska Scenic Views\nYour Agent Vrges Safety\nWhen purchasing an insurance policy, all pro\ntection may seem alike to you.\nBut, later, should you experience a loss, the\nreputation of your agent and your continued\nconfidence in him will depend upon the in\ninsurance protection he has selected for you as\nwell as upon the prompt performance of the\ncompanies he represents.\nAs agents who have built up a sound, depend\nable service, we urge you to insure only where\nyou can have no regrets now\u2014or later.\nAllen Shattuck9 Inc.\nINSURANCE\u2014Every Kind","height":"26288","width":"20268"}}
